One of my favorite restaurants in the city. I heard so many good things about this restaurant. Finally I got a chance to check out Gary Danko on my birthday. The food and services were exultantly well-executed. The 3 course prix pixe were succelent. I didn't like my first pairing wine, the sommelier was kind enough to let me try on another half bottle and charged me nothing on my first bottle. I thought we were going to squander big $$ on the dinner, but it came out pretty reasonable for 2 people. I must say It felt like loyal treatments and 10 times better than La Folie.

Before I began to tell my story DO NOT ORDER THE CHAMPAGNE THEY OFFER IN THE BEGINNING UNLESS YOU ARE WILLING TO PAY $25 - $40 PER GLASS. You have been warned. I finally rolled my fatty ass into this place 3 months ago. It was definitely a special occassion for the manatee (aka Merlion) turning 24 years old. In hindsight its not that special because 24 years is a lame age to turn. She still can't rent a car. Sucka. But it was also a celebration of graduation from grad school and passing boards for my fat self. I am now 50 lbs lighter because I spent too much of my loan money eating at this places and now in the real world I am dead broke. POS. So we arrive on a cold dark night on the wharf. Found some nice parking and walked up the hill with a bottle of Cabernet Franc from Pride Vineyards so I can hopefully save a few bucks in the end. *Note* corkage is $35 so make sure you bring a wine that is actually worth openning here. We sit down and order 2 glass of champagne to start off the night which I will regret later. We decided to do the 5 course meal which I will also regret 4 hours later while we were still eating. Ok, I will now attempt to remember and describe all 10 of the dishes we had that night. Note: Every dish that night was licked clean and given a final check by me. No food here went uneaten! My decisions were not only based on what sounded good but also which looked the most expensive (I'm a fatty azn, its my nature). The pan seared Foie Gras with some sauce reduction was freaking amazing. I've only eaten this stuff less than 5 times in my fatty lifetime and this was by far the best live I have ever eaten. The lobster bisque was very rich and creamy. I was expecting something a not as filling but if you are looking for a rich soup definitely try this one out. But it was a little too much for me. The Day boat scallop was to die for. I am having stomach pangs just thinking about it. Some trio of cerviche or salmon tartar (cant remember) was just ok. I don't remember it therefore it was probably just ok. The poached lobster was good if you like lobster. After eating at the lobster shack in north beach recently I can't stomach lobster anymore. Lobster rolls and airplanes don't mix FYI. The risotto was also really good. It was rich, thick, and creamy The manatee didn't care for it so I ate it. Therefore I had 6 courses. For the main course I wanted to try the lame but I wanted to be daring a eat a new animal. So I had the bison. It was very good. It tasted almost like lamb but not as gamey. It was prepared very nicely. The manatee had a really good main dish. If you read my reviews you probably already know what she ordered. Some kind of sea animal. That night it was the pan seared stripped bass. Omg it was freaking awesome. Good choice Manatee aka Merlion. So by this time we are freaking bursting at the seems when the cheese cart and our dessert comes. I don't remember the cheese nor the dessert because I was in food delirium. By now most people have stopped reading this review because it is so freakin long. 5 courses isn't short people. Since I had to eat most of the Manatee's food it was more like a 10 course for me. If you can write a 5 sentence review for a 10 course meal then you obviously arent fat like me. I probably gained 20 lbs thats night but it was well worth it. Service was excellent and very attentive. I will definitely be back here once I find a sugar mama. UPDATE 10/28/07: I just came back from my second GD experience and I am fatter than fat right now. This is still the best fine dining restaurant you can eat in SF. You won't get 5 courses anywhere for under $100. I love you, Gary. -xoxo PS: Go 5 tasting menu or go eat a salad.

This restaurant was amazing. we celebrated our anniversary there and we had such a great experience. we got 3 main courses and 2 appetizers they were all great we could not even decide which dish was the best. the service was even better than the food. i strongly recommend this place to everyone.

OK, Im gonna say it but only because Miriam W hasn't beaten me to it. so I've eaten their 5 times in the last 4 years. It was my favorite restaurant. Sure, I was always eating there on someone else's dime. Finally the day before Valentine's I took my 2 best friends, my treat. Miriam W leapt and dare I say "YELPED" as the cab turned the corner and stopped at the GD door. She had never been. She was amazed. So amazed that we took a foriegn visitor who had traveled half the world for this in May. And then... Look I don't mean to be a bitch, and we're all human and all but if you are going to be one of the best restaurants in the world and the best in the city that is the epicurean fantasy that SF can be, you simply need to be the best every night. And besides at $200 a person and midnight, who is wanting to be handed it? No, no, no. Who should go here: Everyone that hasn't eaten at Danko, and if you have you should go back. 1 Star - Lacking/Turn Off 2 Stars - Needs Work, But fixable 3 Stars - Adequate 4 Stars - Near perfect, rough edge here or there 5 Stars - Can't get much Better Ambience: 5 Stars. Sophisticated, modern, elegant and comfortable. Finally a world class place that doesn't feel overly stuffy, gaudy (like Minna) or uncomfortable. I prefer the main dining room, as it is where the action is at, and personally I think has better lighting, etc. But the side dining room is nice for a more intimate dining experience. The bar fits snug in between the two dining rooms, and fine if you get a seat, but tough otherwise, as it is one of the main freeways for the waiters. Service: 5 stars+. Can service get any better, if it can I have yet to experience it. I hit Danko roughly 3 times a year, and every single time the service is flawless. Generally you will have a head waiter for the table, but throughout the meal you will be attended to by numerous staff that fulfill your every need. The odd thing about the service here is that you never really know the help is around, yet they are hovering throughout the dining room waiting to attend to even the smallest request. I have never found the staff to be snobby or stiff, only at times serious (not cold). The staff knowledge of the menu is incredible, and you will feel they handle questions on the food as if they are the chef. Food: 5 stars. The menu here changes about 4 or 5 times a year, depending on the season. The style is California cuisine, with a little more French influence than say a Chez Panisse. Every dish uses only the freshest ingredients and is well thought out in terms of delivering the perfect combination of scents, textures in the mouth, and of course, flavors. I am allergic to shell fish, so haven't tried these dishes here, but my dining companions often rave about the various lobster soups/salads and entrees that appear from time to time on the menu. A week ago I started with the Seared foie Gras, incredible, melted in my mouth and the caramelized onions and fuji apples rounded out the silkiness of the foie gras perfectly. Next I moved on to the Pancetta wrapped frog legs. These were very good, a little rich though, but some of the most unusual combination of flavors (but it worked magically). Next I had the pepper crusted venison. If you go there soon, all I will say is get this dish, and I will leave it at that. Next is cheese tray time. Gary Danko maintains one of the most extensive and unique cheese trays, don't pass this up. As far as desert, you can't go wrong, however, I have never gotten sick of the chocolate souffl. Light and airy, and filled with two separate sauces, a white and dark chocolate. I think it should be a requirement that at least one of these per table is ordered. Wine: 5 stars. The wine list is like a book, but very well organized and only contains great bottles. You will never fine off vintages here or sub-par producers. The list ranges from about $50 to over $10,000. Most stuff is over $100, so be prepared for a bit of sticker shock. I usually study the list extensively beforehand and am ready to order before I dine here. But for most what I recommend is taking advantage of the sommelier, and describe what you like in a wine and your price range. You will not be disappointed. Last time there we had the 2001 Cantina del Pino Barbaresco, Ovello. At $82, it was one of the steals on the menu. We then moved on to the 2003 Numanthia at $140. A huge wine that goes better with the red meat entrees. If you love wine, I suggest just perusing the menu, it is a real treat. Overall: 5 stars+. In the 9 times I have dined here, I have never once had a bad or even mediocre experience. Gary Danko is perfection in dining. From service, to food, to the wines be prepared for a spectacular culinary evening. There might be some places that have a bit better food, or maybe a better wine list, but no one puts together the package like Danko. For Friday and Saturday nights I would suggest making a reservation at least 6 wks in advance. For weekdays, 3 to 4 weeks is required at a minimum.

Bonus time at work, had money to burn and been wanting to try out this place I have heard so much about, plus never been to a place this expensiv-o. Well took my girl of the moment and even before we were seated and still en route in the car. "Where are we going?" "Somewhere nice!" "Gary Danko?" "How did you know!?!?" "Not to much other sutff down here, and on a side note, no need to try you will be getting some" Gary Danko = Panty Dropper Food, service and ambiance were excellent too!

Food is becoming a very dangerous thing for my body. My clothes are fitting a little tighter, my pants hugging closer to my hips....tsk tsk. But while on vacation, this is not a concern; it's only until I return home that I begin to regret every chocolate shake and ounce of butter I ate. But Gary Danko, I would never regret you. My bank account might, but I would never forsake you. I took my boyfriend here as a Christmas present since we were planning a get-a-way. Now I know how guys feel. Your significant other is nagging you to go somewhere, so finally you just throw your hands up in the air and give in. But at least this dinner was something I could experience as well. We were brought a complimentary fried oyster with a cucumber relish to start off the meal. I opted for the 3-course, knowing that my boyfriend was going to have to help me finish that. I ordered the lobster salad with a chestnut mousse, persimmons and pomegranate. Drool just came out of my mouth. All of the flavors were paired perfectly with a hint of sweetness and creaminess from the mousse with the tartness of the pomegranate with the lobster. Then I had the coconut thai curry with seafood and lemongrass over rice. To be quite honest if the rice was a sweet sticky rice, the dish would have tasted much better. Oh well, but on to the best dish of the evening were the seared scallops with butternut squash puree, roasted apples, shallots and red pepper. Scallops prepared well are heaven...these melted in your mouth. I think I worked on the two scallops for over 10 minutes because I didn't want to finish it because it was so good. My boyfriend got the 4-course and we shared a dessert which was perfect! He started off with the dungeness crab salad with grapefruit, asian pear and a mint remoulade. Then he had the roast maine lobster with potato puree, chantarelle mushrooms, edamame, and taragon. For his main course, he had the seared filet with spaetzle, butternut squash, crimini mushrooms with a bone marrow butter. To share we had the warm Louisiana butter cake served with a pear ice cream and huckleberry compote. It was good but it literally is warm not hot which I think if it was hot it would have been way better, but still good nonetheless. They also give you a tray filled with mini one-bite desserts which we polished off. They give the ladies a dessert to go which was a pumpkin cheesecake but it was left in a refrigerator when we left SF so we never got to try it! =( The experience took a little over 3 hours, but we were enjoying each other's company and we took our time. The look on my boyfriend's face was priceless and totally worth every penny. If I could afford it, I would eat there everyday. P.S. Their corkage fee is a whopping $35!

However, while looking into other places the reviews of Gary Danko haunted my thoughts and we decided that even though it would be less romantic we would go early and sit at the bar, I am going to go ahead and say that was a brilliant idea, almost better than sitting at a private table! We were served by the most AMAZING bartender, JC, and met a great group of people around us; to our left a couple who frequented the place often and gave us major direction on what to eat (um, is everything an option!), to our right another couple celebrating their anniversary! We chatted, exchanged bites and had the best time. The food was OUT of this WORLD good, best meal ever! I had the fois gras, lobster risotto( so much lobster inside!), Maine lobster and the chocolate soufflé, all choices were OUTRAGEOUSLY good! My husband had (because you can order mains as starters, how fab!?) the pork belly & pork loin, duck ( did they inject this dish with flavor?! so much in every bite!), tenderloin and the trio of creme brûlée. To say which courses were the best is actually insanely hard to do, they were all so freaking amazing that to highlight one or two feels like I am cheating on the rest, and after the way they did me so right last night I could never! My husband had the cocktail with tequila and jalapeño syrup; such intense and diverse flavors hitting your tongue in layers, very complex, very unique! For dessert we just said make us a good coffee cocktail, not sure even what it was but I think JC said there was coconut milk in it and it looked garnished with cherries or cranberries, whatever it was it was fabulous! At the end of our meal I turned to my husband and said, "how will any of our future anniversaries live up to this?! We may have to make this an annual trip!" At Gary Danko food was everything I wanted it to be and more and service was so unpretentious and yet so top notch and classy I was caught off guard by some of their over the top ways to make your experience memorable and special every time. The question isn't should you go to Gary Danko while in SF, but when and how many times!! And just in case you couldn't remember the extent of how fabulous place Gary Danko is they give you a parting gift to eat the next day... even my cat was in my grill trying to get at it! Must get his fine dining tastes from me!

I think the secret to fully enjoying Gary Danko is to somehow go without a shred of expectation. I made the mistake of telling everyone I was going, and how excited I was about it. And everyone who'd ever been there makes that face, you know, that wistful, sweet expression people get when they look at babies, and they say, "Oooh...Gary Danko!" all breathlessly and then they swoon. Okay, they don't swoon. But they extol the virtues of the place like crazy, usually starting with the cheese cart and ending with the service. I was pretty much expecting a transcendent dining experience. I was expecting ambrosia itself. I was expecting perfection. Imagine my disappointment when it was none of these things. Yes, the service was almost impeccable. And the cheese cart was amazing. But the food was not what I had been led to expect--and certainly at those prices, no expectation can be too high. The centerpiece of almost everything we had was blase, unremarkable--while the goodies that accompanied it were usually wonderful. For example, the gratin and mushrooms that came with my steak were delicious, but not delicious enough to save the dry, overcooked beef tenderloin. The lobster risotto was almost great--except the risotto was undercooked. The cauliflower soup with dungeness and hollandaise was surprisingly bland considering all those rich ingredients. We opted for the sommelier-chosen wine pairings with each course, which was nice, but none of the wines really stood out. Our waiter/s (not really sure which of the ten people swarming our table was actually our waiter) were all friendly, but a bit patronizing. (Maybe it was just us?) And having asked permission to bring a couple of bottles of good Belgian beer to dinner and pay a corkage, and having that permission granted by the reservationist, the manager/sommelier was very ungraceful about it--reminding us repeatedly how they were making an exception to their policy for us. If that's the case, then just say no, don't bring beer. Don't tell us we can bring it then act all weird when we do. Anyway, most important, we had a great time. The vibe was good, the meal was luxuriously long, which I love, and the things that were great (cheese cart, scallops, service--mostly, atmosphere, pacing) were truly great. I am hoping that we went on an off night--maybe Gary was vacationing in France, leaving his kitchen in the hands of a young sous chef who, while promisingly talented, still has his off days. Or something like that. I'll be curious to go back... someday.

The first time I came here last year, it was without a question, 5 star service and food. So I didn't think I needed to share my gushing over Gary Danko since my review would have echoed what everyone else has said. To continue the tradition, came here a 2nd time this year. And sad to say, it wasn't nearly as great. The service was still excellent, a wonderful waiter who knew everything about wine. 1st course: foie gras: succulent, easily my favorite course of the evening. the piece wasn't very large, and i could have probably eaten two plates of it, but i don't think that would have been healthy. 2nd course: roast main lobster. very good. half a tail and cooked tenderly. but that's all i remember. 3rd course: and then it started going downhill. i love lobster, so why not continue with a lobster risotto. it was absolutely divine until....in the very dim light, i couldn't tell but upon further inspection, A HAIR in my risotto. Not a super long strand. but it looked like some sous chef's hair fell out and into my plate. it was pretty well hidden in the risotto so i think it must have cooked within. let me say that if i were at a pho restaurant or a chinese restaurant and i found a hair, i'd be like, whatever, you get what you pay for. but at Gary Danko??? Really? Before I alerted our waiter, I made sure to ask my fellow diners if it was truly a hair. After consensus, I flagged the waiter, who was of course very apologetic about it and brought me a fresh plate. But that's about it. I don't want to seem spoiled, but we were a large party, ordered wine with our 5 course meals and were overall very polite. I think we at least deserved a small plate of "I'm sorry there was a hair in your food at this 2-Michelin Star restaurant." Anyway, that was truly disappointing. 4th course: seared filet of beef, medium. i was further disappointed in the flavor of the steak, or lack thereof. it wasn't dry, but it was definitely not seasoned. reaching for salt and pepper mill at home, ok, but at Gary Danko? Did I have too high of expectations? and it came with a potato croquette. don't get me wrong, i love potato croquettes...at my favorite $20 sushi restaurant. it wasn't croquette with truffles. it was a plain old fried potato cake. fine, but boring. 5th course: trio of creme brulee: very good. vanilla, chocolate, and pumpkin. the pumpkin was the best and redeemed the place a little. i would still recommend this dessert. OH! and last but not least...as we're leaving for the night, i went to grab the to-go boxes since some of us were using the restrooms. and the maitre d almost snatched the box out of my hands. "I'll just give this to your colleague when she gets here." Whoa, wait a minute. Do I somehow look like a common thief trying to steal leftovers? Please, give your guests a little more credit than that. I think we'll be ending our tradition here.

    11/29/2006

    Who should go here: Everyone that hasn't eaten at Danko, and if you have you should go back.  

    1 Star - Lacking/Turn Off
    2 Stars - Needs Work, But fixable
    3 Stars - Adequate
    4 Stars - Near perfect, rough edge here or there
    5 Stars - Can't get much Better

    Ambience: 5 Stars.  Sophisticated, modern, elegant and comfortable.  Finally a world class place that doesn't feel overly stuffy, gaudy (like Minna) or uncomfortable.  I prefer the main dining room, as it is where the action is at, and personally I think has better lighting, etc.  But the side dining room is nice for a more intimate dining experience.  The bar  fits snug in between the two dining rooms, and fine if you get a seat, but tough otherwise, as it is one of the main freeways for the waiters.  

    Service: 5 stars+.  Can service get any better, if it can I have yet to experience it.  I hit Danko roughly 3 times a year, and every single time the service is flawless.   Generally you will have a head waiter for the table, but throughout the meal you will be attended to by numerous staff that fulfill your every need.  The odd thing about the service here is that you never really know the help is around, yet they are hovering throughout the dining room waiting to attend to even the smallest request.  I have never found the staff to be snobby or stiff, only at times serious (not cold).  The staff knowledge of the menu is incredible, and you will feel they handle questions on the food as if they are the chef.

    Food: 5 stars.  The menu here changes about 4 or 5 times a year, depending on the season.  The style is California cuisine, with a little more French influence than say a Chez  Panisse.  Every dish uses only the freshest  ingredients and is well thought out in terms of delivering the perfect combination of scents, textures in the mouth, and of course,  flavors.  I am allergic to shell fish, so haven't tried these dishes here, but my dining companions often rave about the various lobster soups/salads and entrees that appear from time to time on the menu.  A week ago I started with the Seared foie Gras, incredible, melted in my mouth and the caramelized onions and fuji apples rounded out the silkiness of the foie gras perfectly.  Next I moved on to the Pancetta wrapped frog legs.  These were very good, a little rich though, but some of the most unusual combination of flavors (but it worked magically).  Next I had the pepper crusted venison.  If you go there soon, all I will say is get this dish, and I will leave it at that.  Next is cheese tray time.  Gary Danko maintains one of the most extensive and unique cheese trays, don't pass this up.  As far as desert, you can't go wrong, however, I have never gotten sick of the chocolate souffl.  Light and airy, and filled with two separate sauces, a white and dark chocolate.  I think it should be a requirement that at least one of these per table is ordered.

    Wine: 5 stars.  The wine list is like a book, but very well organized and only contains great bottles.  You will never fine off vintages here or sub-par producers.  The list ranges from about $50 to over $10,000.  Most stuff is over $100, so be prepared for a bit of sticker shock.  I usually study the list extensively beforehand and am ready to order before I dine here.  But for most what I recommend is taking advantage of the sommelier, and describe what you like in a wine and your price range.   You will not be disappointed.  Last time there we had the 2001 Cantina del Pino Barbaresco, Ovello.  At $82, it was one of the steals on the menu.  We then moved on to the 2003 Numanthia at $140.  A huge wine that goes better with the red meat entrees.  If you love wine, I suggest just perusing the menu, it is a real treat.

    Overall:   5 stars+. In the 9 times I have dined here, I have never once had a bad or even mediocre experience.  Gary Danko is perfection in dining.  From service, to food, to the wines be prepared for a spectacular culinary evening.   There might be some places that have a bit better food, or maybe a better wine list, but no one puts together the package like Danko.  For Friday and Saturday nights I would suggest making a reservation at least 6 wks in advance.  For weekdays, 3 to 4 weeks is required at a minimum.

    Food is becoming a very dangerous thing for my body.  My clothes are fitting a little tighter, my pants hugging closer to my hips....tsk tsk.  But while on vacation, this is not a concern; it's only until I return home that I begin to regret every chocolate shake and ounce of butter I ate.

    But Gary Danko, I would never regret you.  My bank account might, but I would never forsake you.

    I took my boyfriend here as a Christmas present since we were planning a get-a-way.  Now I know how guys feel.  Your significant other is nagging you to go somewhere, so finally you just throw your hands up in the air and give in.  But at least this dinner was something I could experience as well.

    We were brought a complimentary fried oyster with a cucumber relish to start off the meal.  I opted for the 3-course, knowing that my boyfriend was going to have to help me finish that.  I ordered the lobster salad with a chestnut mousse, persimmons and pomegranate.  Drool just came out of my mouth.  All of the flavors were paired perfectly with a hint of sweetness and creaminess from the mousse with the tartness of the pomegranate with the lobster.  Then I had the coconut thai curry with seafood and lemongrass over rice.  To be quite honest if the rice was a sweet sticky rice, the dish would have tasted much better.  Oh well, but on to the best dish of the evening were the seared scallops with butternut squash puree, roasted apples, shallots and red pepper.  Scallops prepared well are heaven...these melted in your mouth.  I think I worked on the two scallops for over 10 minutes because I didn't want to finish it because it was so good.

    My boyfriend got the 4-course and we shared a dessert which was perfect!  He started off with the dungeness crab salad with grapefruit, asian pear and a mint remoulade. Then he had the roast maine lobster with potato puree, chantarelle mushrooms, edamame, and taragon.  For his main course, he had the seared filet with spaetzle, butternut squash, crimini mushrooms with a bone marrow butter.

    To share we had the warm Louisiana butter cake served with a pear ice cream and huckleberry compote.  It was good but it literally is warm not hot which I think if it was hot it would have been way better, but still good nonetheless.  They also give you a tray filled with mini one-bite desserts which we polished off.

    They give the ladies a dessert to go which was a pumpkin cheesecake but it was left in a refrigerator when we left SF so we never got to try it! =(

    The experience took a little over 3 hours, but we were enjoying each other's company and we took our time.  The look on my boyfriend's face was priceless and totally worth every penny.

    If I could afford it, I would eat there everyday.

    P.S. Their corkage fee is a whopping $35!

    I think the secret to fully enjoying Gary Danko is to somehow go without a shred of expectation. I made the mistake of telling everyone I was going, and how excited I was about it. And everyone who'd ever been there makes that face, you know, that wistful, sweet expression people get when they look at babies, and they say, "Oooh...Gary Danko!" all breathlessly and then they swoon. Okay, they don't swoon. But they extol the virtues of the place like crazy, usually starting with the cheese cart and ending with the service.

    I was pretty much expecting  a transcendent dining experience. I was expecting ambrosia itself. I was expecting perfection.

    Imagine my disappointment when it was none of these things.

    Yes, the service was almost impeccable. And the cheese cart was amazing. But the food was not what I had been led to expect--and certainly at those prices, no expectation can be too high. The centerpiece of almost everything we had was blase, unremarkable--while the goodies that accompanied it were usually wonderful. For example, the gratin and mushrooms that came with my steak were delicious, but not delicious enough to save the dry, overcooked beef tenderloin. The lobster risotto was almost great--except the risotto was undercooked. The cauliflower soup with dungeness and hollandaise was surprisingly bland considering all those rich ingredients. We opted for the sommelier-chosen wine pairings with each course, which was nice, but none of the wines really stood out.

    Our waiter/s (not really sure which of the ten people swarming our table was actually our waiter) were all friendly, but a bit patronizing. (Maybe it was just us?) And having asked permission to bring a couple of bottles of good Belgian beer to dinner and pay a corkage, and having that permission granted by the reservationist, the manager/sommelier was very ungraceful about it--reminding us repeatedly how they were making an exception to their policy for us. If that's the case, then just say no, don't bring beer. Don't tell us we can bring it then act all weird when we do.

    Anyway, most important, we had a great time. The vibe was good, the meal was luxuriously long, which I love, and the things that were great  (cheese cart, scallops, service--mostly, atmosphere, pacing) were truly great. I am hoping that we went on an off night--maybe Gary was vacationing in France, leaving his kitchen in the hands of a young sous chef who, while promisingly talented, still has his off days.

    Or something like that.

    I'll be curious to go back... someday.

I don't want to seem spoiled, but we were a large party, ordered wine with our 5 course meals and were overall very polite. I think we at least deserved a small plate of "I'm sorry there was a hair in your food at this 2-Michelin Star restaurant." Anyway, that was truly disappointing.

    4th course: seared filet of beef, medium. i was further disappointed in the flavor of the steak, or lack thereof. it wasn't dry, but it was definitely not seasoned. reaching for salt and pepper mill at home, ok, but at Gary Danko? Did I have too high of expectations? and it came with a potato croquette. don't get me wrong, i love potato croquettes...at my favorite $20 sushi restaurant. it wasn't croquette with truffles. it was a plain old fried potato cake. fine, but boring.

    5th course: trio of creme brulee: very good. vanilla, chocolate, and pumpkin. the pumpkin was the best and redeemed the place a little. i would still recommend this dessert.

    OH! and last but not least...as we're leaving for the night, i went to grab the to-go boxes since some of us were using the restrooms. and the maitre d almost snatched the box out of my hands. "I'll just give this to your colleague when she gets here." Whoa, wait a minute. Do I somehow look like a common thief trying to steal leftovers? Please, give your guests a little more credit than that.

    I think we'll be ending our tradition here.
